def L(lv,t,c,code='',tip=''):return(lv,t,c,code,tip)
CPP=[
L(1,'What is C++?','C++ is a high-performance language used for games, operating systems, embedded systems, and applications where speed matters. It gives you direct control over memory and hardware. C++ was created by Bjarne Stroustrup as an extension of C — the "++" means "one step beyond C."','#include <iostream>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n    cout << "Hello, World!" << endl;\n    return 0;\n}','Every C++ program needs a main() function — it is where execution begins. return 0 tells the operating system the program ran successfully.'),
L(1,'#include and Namespace','The #include directive imports library headers. <iostream> provides input/output with cout and cin. using namespace std lets you use standard library features without typing std:: before each one.','#include <iostream>  // input/output\n#include <string>    // string type\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n    string name = "Alice";\n    cout << "Hello, " << name << endl;\n    return 0;\n}','Without using namespace std, you must write std::cout, std::string, std::endl everywhere. The namespace avoids this repetition.'),
L(2,'Variables and Types','C++ is statically typed — every variable must declare its type at creation. Built-in types: int (integers), double (decimals), float (smaller decimals), char (single character), bool (true/false), string (text).','int age = 25;\ndouble price = 9.99;\nchar letter = \'A\';\nbool active = true;\nstring name = "Alice";\n\nauto x = 42;  // compiler deduces: int','auto lets the compiler figure out the type. It\'s handy for complex types, but keep simple types explicit for readability.'),
L(2,'Constants','Use const for values that should never change after initialization. constexpr means the value is known at compile time and can be used where compile-time constants are required.','const double PI = 3.14159;\nconstexpr int MAX_SIZE = 100;\n\n// These will NOT compile:\n// PI = 3.0;      // Error: const\n// MAX_SIZE = 50;  // Error: constexpr\n\ncout << "PI = " << PI << endl;','Convention: ALL_CAPS for constants (PI, MAX_SIZE) to visually distinguish them from variables in your code.'),
L(3,'Operators','C++ has arithmetic (+, -, *, /, %), comparison (==, !=, <, >), logical (&&, ||, !), and bitwise (&, |, ^) operators. Integer division truncates: 10/3 gives 3, not 3.33.','int a = 10, b = 3;\ncout << a / b << endl;    // 3 (integer!)\ncout << a % b << endl;    // 1 (remainder)\ncout << (a > b) << endl;  // 1 (true)\n\nbool result = (a > 5) && (b < 10); // true','In C++, true is 1 and false is 0. Any non-zero value is treated as true in boolean context. cout prints booleans as 1 or 0.'),
L(3,'Input and Output','Use cout with << for output and cin with >> for input. cin >> stops reading at whitespace (spaces). Use getline(cin, variable) to read an entire line including spaces.','string name;\ncout << "Enter your name: ";\ngetline(cin, name);\n\nint age;\ncout << "Enter your age: ";\ncin >> age;\n\ncout << "Hello, " << name\n     << "! Age: " << age << endl;','cin >> stops at whitespace: entering "John Smith" would only store "John". Use getline() when you need to read full sentences or names with spaces.'),
L(4,'String Operations','C++ strings support concatenation (+), comparison (==, <, >), length(), substr(), find(), and append. Use s[0] to access individual characters by index.','string s = "Hello World";\ncout << s.length() << endl;     // 11\ncout << s.substr(0, 5) << endl;  // Hello\ncout << s.find("World") << endl; // 6\n\ns += "!";  // append\ncout << s << endl;  // Hello World!','Use s.empty() instead of s.length() == 0 to check for empty strings — it is cleaner and communicates your intent better.'),
L(4,'String Comparison','Strings can be compared with ==, !=, <, and > operators. Comparison is lexicographic (dictionary order) and case-sensitive. Uppercase letters come before lowercase in ASCII.','string a = "apple";\nstring b = "banana";\n\nif (a == b) cout << "Same";\nif (a < b)  cout << "a comes first";\n// Output: a comes first\n\n// Case-sensitive:\ncout << ("Apple" < "apple");  // 1 (true)','Uppercase letters have lower ASCII values: \'A\' is 65, \'a\' is 97. So "Apple" < "apple" is true because A (65) < a (97).'),
L(5,'Arrays','C++ arrays have a fixed size determined at creation. Elements are accessed by zero-based index. Arrays do NOT track their own size — you must remember it or calculate it with sizeof.','int nums[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};\ncout << nums[0] << endl;  // 10\nnums[2] = 99;\n\n// Loop through\nfor (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {\n    cout << nums[i] << " ";\n}','Accessing an out-of-bounds index (like nums[10] in a 5-element array) is undefined behavior — C++ does NOT throw an exception, it just corrupts memory silently.'),
L(5,'Vectors — Dynamic Arrays','Vectors from <vector> are dynamic arrays that grow automatically. They are safer and more flexible than raw arrays, with methods like push_back(), pop_back(), size(), and at() for bounds-checked access.','#include <vector>\n\nvector<int> nums = {1, 2, 3};\nnums.push_back(4);        // add to end\nnums.pop_back();          // remove last\ncout << nums.size();      // 3\ncout << nums[0];          // 1\n\nfor (int n : nums) {\n    cout << n << " ";\n}','Prefer vectors over raw arrays in modern C++. They manage memory automatically, track their size, and work with the standard library algorithms.'),
L(6,'If/Else and Switch','Use if/else for conditional branching. Switch compares one value against multiple constants. Always include break in switch cases — without it, execution falls through to the next case.','int score = 85;\nif (score >= 90) {\n    cout << "A";\n} else if (score >= 80) {\n    cout << "B";\n} else {\n    cout << "C";\n}\n\nswitch (score / 10) {\n    case 10: case 9: cout << "A"; break;\n    case 8: cout << "B"; break;\n    default: cout << "C";\n}','Missing break causes fall-through: case 8 would also execute case 7, case 6, etc. Always add break unless you intentionally want fall-through (rare).'),
L(6,'Short-Circuit Evaluation','Logical operators && and || stop evaluating as soon as the result is determined. This is used for safe null checks — check if a pointer is valid before dereferencing it.','int* ptr = nullptr;\n\n// Safe: second part skipped if ptr is null\nif (ptr != nullptr && *ptr > 0) {\n    cout << "Positive";\n}\n\n// Ternary operator\nstring name = input.empty() ?\n    "Guest" : input;','Short-circuit prevents crashes: if ptr is nullptr, the && skips *ptr > 0 (which would crash). Always check pointers before dereferencing.'),
L(7,'For and While Loops','Use for when you know the iteration count. Use while for condition-based looping. The range-based for loop (for each) iterates over containers cleanly without tracking indexes.','// Standard for loop\nfor (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {\n    cout << i << " ";\n}\n\n// Range-based for (C++11)\nvector<int> v = {1, 2, 3};\nfor (int n : v) {\n    cout << n << " ";\n}\n\n// While loop\nint x = 10;\nwhile (x > 0) { x--; }','The range-based for loop (for (int n : v)) was added in C++11. It is the clearest way to iterate over containers in modern C++.'),
L(7,'Loop Control','break exits a loop immediately. continue skips to the next iteration. Do-while loops guarantee at least one execution because the condition is checked AFTER the body runs.','// Skip even numbers\nfor (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n    if (i % 2 == 0) continue;\n    cout << i << " ";  // 1 3 5 7 9\n}\n\n// Do-while: runs at least once\nint x;\ndo {\n    cout << "Enter positive: ";\n    cin >> x;\n} while (x <= 0);','Do-while is perfect for input validation: ask for input at least once, then repeat if the input was invalid.'),
L(8,'Functions','Functions are declared with a return type, name, and parameter list. Use void for functions that return nothing. Parameters with default values must come after required parameters.','int add(int a, int b) {\n    return a + b;\n}\n\nvoid greet(string name) {\n    cout << "Hello, " << name << endl;\n}\n\n// Default parameter\ndouble area(double r, double pi = 3.14) {\n    return pi * r * r;\n}','Functions must be declared before they are called. Either define them above main() or use forward declarations (function prototypes) in header files.'),
L(8,'Pass by Reference','By default, functions receive COPIES of arguments (pass by value). Use & to pass by reference — the function works on the original variable. Use const& for read-only access to large objects.','// Pass by value: copy, original unchanged\nvoid doubleVal(int x) { x *= 2; }\n\n// Pass by reference: modifies original\nvoid doubleRef(int& x) { x *= 2; }\n\nint n = 5;\ndoubleVal(n);  // n is still 5\ndoubleRef(n);  // n is now 10','Use const& for large objects you only need to read: void print(const string& s). This avoids expensive copying while preventing accidental modification.'),
L(9,'Pointers','A pointer stores the memory address of a variable. Declare with * (int* ptr), get an address with & (&variable), and access the value at an address with * (*ptr, called dereferencing).','int x = 42;\nint* ptr = &x;  // ptr holds address of x\n\ncout << ptr << endl;   // memory address\ncout << *ptr << endl;  // 42 (value at address)\n\n*ptr = 100;  // changes x through pointer\ncout << x << endl;  // 100','Always initialize pointers. An uninitialized pointer holds a garbage address — dereferencing it causes undefined behavior (crashes, corruption, or seemingly random bugs).'),
L(9,'nullptr and Dynamic Memory','Use nullptr for pointers that do not point to anything (never use NULL or 0 in modern C++). Dynamic memory uses new to allocate and delete to free. Every new MUST have a matching delete.','int* ptr = nullptr;\n\nif (ptr != nullptr) {\n    cout << *ptr;\n} else {\n    cout << "Pointer is null";\n}\n\n// Dynamic memory\nint* arr = new int[5];\n// ... use arr ...\ndelete[] arr;  // free memory','Every new must have a matching delete (or delete[] for arrays). Forgetting delete causes memory leaks. Smart pointers (next lessons) solve this automatically.'),
L(10,'Classes','Classes bundle data (fields) and functions (methods) together. Members are private by default — use public: to expose them. The initializer list is the preferred way to set fields in constructors.','class Rectangle {\nprivate:\n    double width, height;\npublic:\n    Rectangle(double w, double h)\n        : width(w), height(h) {}\n    \n    double area() const {\n        return width * height;\n    }\n};\n\nRectangle r(5.0, 3.0);\ncout << r.area();  // 15','The initializer list (: width(w), height(h)) is more efficient than assignment in the body. const on methods means they do not modify the object.'),
L(10,'Constructors and Destructors','Constructors initialize objects. The destructor (~ClassName) runs automatically when an object goes out of scope, cleaning up resources. This pattern (RAII) is core to C++ resource management.','class FileHandler {\n    string filename;\npublic:\n    FileHandler(string name)\n        : filename(name) {\n        cout << "Opening " << name;\n    }\n    ~FileHandler() {\n        cout << "Closing " << filename;\n    }\n};\n\n{\n    FileHandler f("data.txt");\n}  // destructor called here','RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization): acquire resources in constructors, release in destructors. This prevents resource leaks automatically.'),
L(11,'Inheritance','Child classes inherit public/protected members from a parent using : public ParentName. Use virtual for methods that can be overridden. Use override on child methods to make intent clear and catch typos.','class Shape {\npublic:\n    virtual double area() const = 0;\n    virtual ~Shape() = default;\n};\n\nclass Circle : public Shape {\n    double radius;\npublic:\n    Circle(double r) : radius(r) {}\n    double area() const override {\n        return 3.14159 * radius * radius;\n    }\n};','A pure virtual function (= 0) makes the class abstract — you cannot create instances of it. Every child must implement pure virtual methods.'),
L(11,'Virtual Functions and Polymorphism','Virtual functions enable polymorphism: calling a method through a base class pointer/reference executes the version from the actual derived class. This is how C++ achieves runtime dispatch.','void printArea(const Shape& s) {\n    cout << s.area() << endl;\n}\n\nCircle c(5.0);\nRectangle r(3.0, 4.0);\nprintArea(c);  // calls Circle::area\nprintArea(r);  // calls Rectangle::area','Without virtual, the base class version would always be called regardless of the actual object type. virtual enables correct dispatch.'),
L(12,'Dynamic Memory: new/delete','new allocates memory on the heap (persists beyond scope). delete frees it. Use delete[] for arrays allocated with new[]. Forgetting delete causes memory leaks.','int* p = new int(42);\ncout << *p;  // 42\ndelete p;\n\nint* arr = new int[100];\nfor (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) arr[i] = i;\ndelete[] arr;  // use delete[] for arrays!','delete frees a single object. delete[] frees an array. Mixing them up is undefined behavior — always match new with delete and new[] with delete[].'),
L(12,'Stack vs Heap Memory','Stack memory is fast and automatic — local variables are allocated on the stack and freed when they go out of scope. Heap memory (via new) is flexible and persistent but requires manual management (or smart pointers).','// Stack: automatic, fast, limited size\nvoid func() {\n    int x = 10;         // stack\n    string s = "hello"; // stack\n}  // auto-freed at }\n\n// Heap: manual, flexible\nvoid func2() {\n    int* p = new int(10); // heap\n    delete p;             // must free manually\n}','Prefer stack allocation when possible — it is faster, safer, and automatically cleaned up. Use heap only when objects need to outlive their creating scope.'),
L(13,'unique_ptr — Exclusive Ownership','unique_ptr owns a resource exclusively — when it goes out of scope, the memory is automatically freed. No delete needed. Use make_unique<T>() to create them. They CANNOT be copied, only moved.','#include <memory>\n\nauto ptr = make_unique<int>(42);\ncout << *ptr;  // 42\n// No delete needed!\n\n// For arrays\nauto arr = make_unique<int[]>(5);\narr[0] = 10;','unique_ptr replaces raw new/delete for single-owner resources. It cannot be copied (no shared ownership) — use std::move() to transfer ownership.'),
L(13,'shared_ptr — Shared Ownership','shared_ptr allows multiple pointers to share ownership of the same resource. An internal reference count tracks owners. Memory is freed automatically when the LAST shared_ptr is destroyed.','auto p1 = make_shared<string>("Hello");\nauto p2 = p1;  // both own the string\n\ncout << p1.use_count();  // 2\np1.reset();              // p1 releases\ncout << p2.use_count();  // 1\ncout << *p2;             // "Hello"','Prefer unique_ptr when only one owner is needed (most cases). shared_ptr has overhead from reference counting — only use it when multiple owners are genuinely required.'),
L(14,'Function Templates','Templates write generic code that works with any type. The compiler generates separate versions for each type used. This gives you the flexibility of generics with zero runtime cost.','template <typename T>\nT findMax(T a, T b) {\n    return (a > b) ? a : b;\n}\n\ncout << findMax(10, 20);      // 20\ncout << findMax(3.14, 2.71);  // 3.14\ncout << findMax(\'a\', \'z\');    // z','Templates are resolved at compile time — the compiler generates findMax<int>, findMax<double>, etc. separately. This means zero runtime overhead.'),
L(14,'Class Templates','Template classes work with any type using <T>. The entire STL (vector, map, set, etc.) is built with class templates. Define type-independent data structures once, use with any type.','template <typename T>\nclass Stack {\n    vector<T> data;\npublic:\n    void push(const T& val) {\n        data.push_back(val);\n    }\n    T pop() {\n        T val = data.back();\n        data.pop_back();\n        return val;\n    }\n    bool empty() { return data.empty(); }\n};','The entire C++ Standard Template Library is built with templates. Understanding templates unlocks vector<T>, map<K,V>, set<T>, and all STL algorithms.'),
L(15,'Lambda Expressions','Lambdas are anonymous functions defined inline. The capture clause [] specifies which outer variables are available: [=] captures all by value, [&] by reference, [x, &y] mixes both.','auto add = [](int a, int b) {\n    return a + b;\n};\ncout << add(3, 4);  // 7\n\n// Capture variables from scope\nint factor = 10;\nauto multiply = [factor](int x) {\n    return x * factor;\n};\ncout << multiply(5);  // 50','[=] captures all by value (read-only copy). [&] captures all by reference (can modify). [x, &y] captures x by value and y by reference.'),
L(15,'Move Semantics','Move semantics transfer resources instead of copying them using std::move(). This avoids expensive deep copies for temporary objects and is one of the most important C++11 performance features.','string s1 = "Hello World";\nstring s2 = move(s1);\n// s1 is now empty, s2 has the data\n\n// Move into containers\nvector<string> v;\nv.push_back(move(s2));','After std::move(), the source object is in a "moved-from" state — it is valid but its contents are unspecified. Do not use moved-from objects without reassigning them.'),
]
